on-deterministic: the same review produces varied valid explanations, but all must reference actual input text. Only a real LLM test catches this failure mode.","test_description":"Provide reviews with distinctive, unlikely-to-template phrases (e.g., 'the whizbang feature stopped working'). Call the explanation analyzer and verify the explanation references or echoes that phrase via substring match or semantic similarity. Test multiple reviews with distinct unusual phrases; verify each explanation cites its corresponding review, not a generic template. Confirm explanation does not repeat the same boilerplate text across different inputs.","plan_consistent":true,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.1,"Integration":0.25,"System":0.05,"Agentic":0.6,"Workflow":0}},{"behavior_id":3,"description":"When a review contains both positive and negative keywords, the sentiment score reflects the configured tie-breaking rule (e.g., 'negative priority', 'longer list wins', explicit priority order)","minimum_level":"Unit","justification":"This tests the keyword analyzer's tie-breaking logic, which is pure computation with no I/O or external dependencies. The analyzer receives configured rules as parameters and must apply them consistently. Mocking would hide bugs in rule application: wrong priority, off-by-one errors in list comparison, or failure to apply the rule at all. A unit test directly exercises this logic with real analyzer code.","test_description":"Create a test review with equal counts of positive and negative configured keywords (e.g., 3 positive + 3 negative). Run with tie-breaker 'negative priority' and verify negative sentiment; run with 'positive priority' and verify positive. Test 'longer list wins' with 4 positives and 3 negatives, verify correct outcome. Test boundary case: exactly balanced with each rule option. Verify each configuration produces the expected result.","plan_consistent":true,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.8,"Integration":0.12,"System":0.05,"Agentic":0.03,"Workflow":0}},{"behavior_id":4,"description":"Sentiment analyzer correctly identifies negative polarity of sarcastic reviews (e.g., 'Great, another broken feature') that contain positive surface words but negative underlying intent","minimum_level":"Unit","justification":"Sarcasm detection is likely implemented via heuristic rules (e.g., 'positive word followed by negative-context pattern within N tokens') or a dedicated classifier component, not an expensive LLM call per review. If heuristic-based, a unit test can exercise the detection logic directly. Mocking would hide bugs in the detection pattern: the mock could always claim 'Great, [anything]' is negative without actually implementing sarcasm logic. A unit test with real sarcasm examples directly tests whether polarity is correctly reversed.","test_description":"Pass sarcasm examples to analyzer: 'Great, another bug' (expect negative), 'Wonderful, it's broken again' (expect negative), 'Fantastic, same issue' (expect negative). Pass control cases: 'Great product' (expect positive), 'Broken again' (expect negative). Verify surface-level positive keywords do not override sarcasm detection. Test edge cases: sarcasm marker distant from positive word, negation patterns ('not great'), complex sarcasm structures.","plan_consistent":true,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.5,"Integration":0.08,"System":0.02,"Agentic":0.4,"Workflow":0}},{"behavior_id":5,"description":"Both sentiment score and explanation are returned together in a single response, with the explanation's sentiment direction (positive/negative/neutral) matching the sentiment direction of the score","minimum_level":"Integration","justification":"This test requires both the keyword analyzer (score) and explanation analyzer to run and their outputs to be assembled and verified for consistency. Mocking either component hides failures in response bundling, formatting, or cross-component consistency checks. Real failure modes include: response structure is invalid, outputs are mismatched, or bundling logic fails. If the explanation is LLM-generated, this becomes Agentic (real model calls); if deterministic, Integration level catches all bundling and consistency failures.","test_description":"Provide a clearly positive review to the full service; verify response contains both score and explanation, score indicates positive, explanation text conveys positive sentiment. Repeat for clearly negative and neutral reviews. Test mixed signals (tie-breaker decides) and sarcasm (explanation correctly identifies negative despite positive words). Verify all response fields are present, non-null, and properly formatted. Run multiple distinct reviews to confirm consistency holds across inputs.","plan_consistent":true,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.1,"Integration":0.6,"System":0.03,"Agentic":0.25,"Workflow":0.02}}]},"caller":{"type":"direct"}}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":10,"cache_creation_input_tokens":13527,"cache_read_input_tokens":0,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":13527},"output_tokens":4,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"18312117-eb26-4896-8156-e9bc709e6c48","uuid":"e4a90481-ae40-45a7-946b-4ce4c3d5dca9"}
